### Async Offset Commit with Retry

```java
public class AsyncCommitWithRetry {
    static class RetryableOffsetCommitCallback implements OffsetCommitCallback {
        private KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer;
        private int retries;

        RetryableOffsetCommitCallback(KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer) {
            this.consumer = consumer;
            this.retries = 0;
        }

        @Override
        public void onComplete(Map<TopicPartition, OffsetAndMetadata> offsets,
                              Exception exception) {
            if (exception == null) {
                System.out.println("Commit succeeded for offsets: " + offsets);
                return;
            }

            if (exception instanceof RetriableCommitFailedException && retries < 3) {
                retries++;
                System.out.println("Retriable failure, retrying... (attempt " + retries + ")");
                consumer.commitAsync(offsets, this);  // Retry
            } else {
                System.err.println("Permanent or too many retries: " + exception.getMessage());
                // Log and move on - cannot safely retry
            }
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "my-group");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringDeserializer.class);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringDeserializer.class);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, "false");

        KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
        consumer.subscribe(Collections.singleton("orders"));

        try {
            while (true) {
                ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(1));

                for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                    System.out.println("Message: " + record.value());
                }

                // Async commit with retry callback
                if (records.count() > 0) {
                    consumer.commitAsync(new RetryableOffsetCommitCallback(consumer));
                }
            }
        } finally {
            // Final sync commit before closing
            consumer.commitSync();
            consumer.close();
        }
    }
}
```

### Error Handling and Recovery

```java
public class RobustConsumer {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "my-group");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringDeserializer.class);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringDeserializer.class);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.AUTO_OFFSET_RESET_CONFIG, "earliest");

        KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
        consumer.subscribe(Collections.singleton("orders"));

        try {
            while (true) {
                try {
                    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(1));

                    for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                        try {
                            processOrder(record);
                        } catch (RecordDeserializationException e) {
                            // Bad record - skip it
                            System.err.println("Skipping bad record at " + e.offset());
                            consumer.seek(e.topicPartition(), e.offset() + 1);
                        }
                    }

                    consumer.commitSync();

                } catch (OffsetOutOfRangeException e) {
                    System.err.println("Offset out of range, seeking to end");
                    consumer.seekToEnd(e.partitions());

                } catch (NoOffsetForPartitionException e) {
                    System.err.println("No committed offset, seeking to beginning");
                    consumer.seekToBeginning(e.partitions());

                } catch (WakeupException e) {
                    System.out.println("Shutdown requested");
                    break;

                } catch (KafkaException e) {
                    System.err.println("Kafka error: " + e.getMessage());
                    // Log and continue
                }
            }
        } finally {
            consumer.close();
        }
    }

    static void processOrder(ConsumerRecord<String, String> record) {
        // Simulate processing that may fail
        System.out.println("Processing: " + record.value());
    }
}
```

---

## Best Practices and Patterns

### 1. Always Close Consumers

```java
// BAD: Connection leak if exception occurs
KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
consumer.subscribe(topics);
ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(1));
consumer.close();

// GOOD: Try-with-resources (Java 7+)
try (KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props)) {
    consumer.subscribe(topics);
    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(1));
    // auto-closed
}

// GOOD: Try-finally
KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
try {
    consumer.subscribe(topics);
    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(1));
} finally {
    consumer.close();
}
```

### 2. Handle Rebalancing Gracefully

```java
// GOOD: Implement ConsumerRebalanceListener
consumer.subscribe(topics, new ConsumerRebalanceListener() {
    @Override
    public void onPartitionsRevoked(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
        // Commit pending offsets before losing partitions
        try {
            consumer.commitSync();
        } catch (CommitFailedException e) {
            log.error("Failed to commit during rebalance", e);
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void onPartitionsAssigned(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
        // Restore state for newly assigned partitions
        // Can use consumer.seek() or query external offset store
    }
});
```

### 3. Choose Appropriate Offset Commit Strategy

**Auto-commit (default):** Use when at-least-once semantics acceptable
```java
props.put(ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, "true");
props.put(ConsumerConfig.AUTO_COMMIT_INTERVAL_MS_CONFIG, "1000");
// Simple but risky for critical data
```

**Manual sync commit:** Use for exactly-once semantics
```java
props.put(ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, "false");
// Process records
consumer.commitSync();  // Blocks until broker confirms
```

**Manual async commit:** Use for high throughput with at-least-once
```java
props.put(ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, "false");
consumer.commitAsync((offsets, exception) -> {
    if (exception != null) log.error("Commit failed", exception);
});
```

### 4. Graceful Shutdown

```java
public class ConsumerRunnable implements Runnable {
    private final KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer;
    private final AtomicBoolean shutdown = new AtomicBoolean(false);

    public ConsumerRunnable(KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer) {
        this.consumer = consumer;
    }

    @Override
    public void run() {
        try {
            consumer.subscribe(Collections.singleton("orders"));

            while (!shutdown.get()) {
                try {
                    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records =
                        consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(1));

                    for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                        processRecord(record);
                    }

                    consumer.commitSync();
                } catch (WakeupException e) {
                    if (!shutdown.get()) throw e;
                }
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            log.error("Error in consumer loop", e);
        } finally {
            consumer.commitSync();
            consumer.close();
        }
    }

    public void shutdown() {
        shutdown.set(true);
        consumer.wakeup();  // Wake up blocked poll()
    }

    private void processRecord(ConsumerRecord<String, String> record) {
        // Implementation
    }
}

// Usage
ConsumerRunnable consumerRunnable = new ConsumerRunnable(consumer);
Thread consumerThread = new Thread(consumerRunnable);
consumerThread.start();

// Later, shutdown gracefully
consumerRunnable.shutdown();
consumerThread.join();
```

### 5. Use Pause/Resume for Backpressure

```java
BlockingQueue<ConsumerRecord<String, String>> queue = new LinkedBlockingQueue<>(100);

// Consumer thread: pause when queue full
while (true) {
    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(1));

    for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
        try {
            queue.put(record);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
            break;
        }
    }

    // Check queue capacity and pause if needed
    if (queue.size() > 80) {  // 80% of 100
        TopicPartition tp = new TopicPartition(record.topic(), record.partition());
        consumer.pause(Collections.singleton(tp));
    }
}

// Worker threads: resume when queue drains
new Thread(() -> {
    while (true) {
        try {
            ConsumerRecord<String, String> record = queue.take();
            processRecord(record);

            if (queue.size() < 20) {  // Resume when < 20% full
                Set<TopicPartition> paused = consumer.paused();
                if (!paused.isEmpty()) {
                    consumer.resume(paused);
                }
            }
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
            break;
        }
    }
}).start();
```

### 6. Monitoring and Metrics

```java
ScheduledExecutorService scheduler = Executors.newScheduledThreadPool(1);

scheduler.scheduleAtFixedRate(() -> {
    // Print metrics every 10 seconds
    consumer.metrics().forEach((name, metric) -> {
        if (name.name().contains("lag") || name.name().contains("committed")) {
            System.out.printf("%s: %s%n", name, metric.metricValue());
        }
    });
}, 0, 10, TimeUnit.SECONDS);

// Shutdown scheduler
scheduler.shutdown();
scheduler.awaitTermination(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
```

### 7. Testing with MockConsumer

```java
@Test
public void testConsumerProcessing() {
    MockConsumer<String, String> consumer = new MockConsumer<>();
    TopicPartition partition = new TopicPartition("orders", 0);

    // Simulate partition assignment
    consumer.assign(Collections.singleton(partition));
    consumer.updateBeginningOffsets(Collections.singletonMap(partition, 0L));

    // Add test records
    consumer.addRecord(new ConsumerRecord<>(
        "orders", 0, 0, "order-1", "{ \"id\": 1 }"
    ));
    consumer.addRecord(new ConsumerRecord<>(
        "orders", 0, 1, "order-2", "{ \"id\": 2 }"
    ));

    // Test consumption
    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(1));
    assertEquals(2, records.count());

    // Simulate offset commit
    consumer.commitSync();
    assertTrue(consumer.committed(Collections.singleton(partition)).containsKey(partition));
}
```

### 8. Separate Threading Models

```java
// GOOD: Single-threaded consumer, multi-threaded processing
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(10);

try (KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props)) {
    consumer.subscribe(topics);

    while (running) {
        ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(1));

        for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
            // Submit to thread pool (don't call consumer methods from executor threads)
            executor.submit(() -> processRecord(record));
        }
    }
}

executor.shutdown();
executor.awaitTermination(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
```

**Key constraint:** Only call consumer methods from consumer thread. Use queues to communicate with processing threads.

---

## Summary of Key Behavioral Semantics

1. **Thread Safety:** NOT thread-safe except `wakeup()`. All operations must occur on a single thread.

2. **poll() Semantics:**
   - Returns immediately if records available or timeout expires
   - Can block longer than timeout if rebalance callbacks execute
   - Handles heartbeats, metadata refresh, rebalance coordination

3. **Offset Commits:**
   - Auto-commit fires during `poll()` BEFORE records returned to user
   - Sync commit blocks until broker response
   - Async commit returns immediately, callback invoked later
   - Position advances independently of commits

4. **Rebalancing:**
   - Triggered by group/subscription changes, timeouts, or explicit call
   - Occurs during `poll()` calls
   - Callbacks execute: revoke → rebalance → assign
   - State updates despite callback exceptions

5. **Position vs Committed:**
   - Position: offset of next record to fetch (auto-advances on poll)
   - Committed: last durable offset (set via commit)
   - Committed should = next offset to read after restart

6. **Error Recovery:**
   - OffsetOutOfRange: seek to valid offset
   - NoOffsetForPartition: seek to beginning/end or use auto.offset.reset
   - RecordDeserializationException: position stops at bad record (can skip)
   - CommitFailedException: cannot retry (state unknown)

7. **Wakeup Semantics:**
   - Only exception safe to call from outside consumer thread
   - Interrupts blocking poll() without advancing offset
   - Used for graceful shutdown

8. **Group Management:**
   - max.poll.interval.ms: enforce frequent polling
   - session.timeout.ms: detect dead consumers
   - Heartbeat separate from polling (sent in background)

